ABSTRACT 

Although smartphones have emerged as the primary tool for environmental health research due to their portability and prevalence, the literature has not thoroughly explored their application in assessing location based aggregated air quality indices based on *PM*2*.*5 concentration. Consequently, our study comprehensively analyses the difficulties involved in forecasting *PM*2*.*5 concentrations at a designated site utilising pictures obtained from smartphone cameras. Our study focuses on Dhaka, Bangladesh’s capital, because a substantial portion of its population is subjected to elevated air pollution levels. In this study, we’ve developed a Deep Convolutional Neural Network (DCNN) and trained it using an open-source dataset of more than a thousand outdoor pictures taken at various locations in Dhaka, Bangladesh. The NowCast algorithm was used to categorize them based on *PM*2*.*5 concentration information from the nearby US consulate. The model’s ability to operate as a Picture-based Predictor of *PM*2*.*5 Concentration (PPPC) is improved by obtaining a correlation index using supervised learning during training with the dataset. Our model predicts daily averaged Air Quality Index (AQI) from smartphone photos. It uses fewer parameters compared to other models. Tests show it outperforms VGG19, ResNet50, and MobileNetV2. It surpasses advanced models like the Involutional Neural Network (INN) and Vision Transformer (ViT). Deep learning models are often seen as black-box systems. This limits their interpretability and trust. To address this, we used Explainable AI (XAI) techniques. These methods reveal the parts of an image that influence the model’s predictions. This improves its transparency and reliability. Since our methodology depends on mobile-based picture predictions, it is essential to guarantee that the model acquires the appropriate information and generates precise predictions accordingly. We utilised LIME and GRAD-CAM Explainable Artificial Intelligence (XAI) to improve the interpretability of our model. 

Keywords: Air Quality Index, Picture-based Predictor of *PM*2*.*5 Concentration (PPPC), deep learning, regression modelling, deep learning, Environmental Health.

Chapter 1 

Introduction 

1.1 Overview 

Millions of fatalities are attributed to poor air quality each year, making air pollution a severe worldwide health concern. Urban areas like Dhaka, Bangladesh, are particularly affected \[1\] \[2\]. The need for accessible and reliable air quality monitoring using everyday technologies is the motivation behind this work. Due to their portability and advanced cameras, smartphones have been widely used. These features provide a unique opportunity for cost-effective and scalable air quality monitoring. This thesis focuses on developing a deep learning approach to predict a location’s Air Quality Index (AQI) from smartphone images. The method uses DCNNS to identify some pattern from the captured images for predict the *PM*2*.*5 concentration which is a major health risk and air pollution. The combination of the smartphone-captured images and official AQI data develops a predictor which is known as Picture-based *PM*2*.*5 Concentration Predictor (PC) \[3\] which has a goal to improve the air quality information accessibility to the urban people. 

1.2 Motivation and Research Problem 

Air pollutants contain harmful elements like particulate matter (PM), gases, and vapor molecules in the atmosphere, which pose acute health risks.\[4\]. According to the World Health Organization (WHO), millions die annually because of air pollution. Alarmingly, almost 90% people breathe air that exceeds the WHO’s recommended quality. Low and middle-income countries bear the heaviest burden \[5\]. The 11th aim of the United Nations (UN) Sustainable Development Goals (SDG) emphasizes the importance of critical services and sufficient, safe, and affordable living circumstances. Air quality

Chapter 2 

Literature Review 

2.1 Ambient air pollutants 

Air pollution consists of 6 principal pollutants, and these are \- particulate matter (*PM*10 and *PM*2*.*5), sulfur dioxide (*SO*2), ground-level ozone (*O*3), nitrogen dioxide (*NO*2), lead (Pb), and carbon monoxide (CO). \[19\]. *PM*2*.*5, composed of fine particulate matter, poses significant health risks by penetrating the lungs and circulation, resulting in severe respiratory and cardiovascular diseases (Pope *et al.*, 2009; WHO, 2018\) \[20, 21\]. This may lead to respiratory complications (Bell *et al.*, 2006)\[22\]. Carbon monoxide, an incomplete combustion byproduct of fossil fuels, can impair oxygen transport in the bloodstream, consequently reducing oxygen availability to the body’s organs and tissues, which may lead to adverse health effects (WHO, 2010; EPA, 2016)\[23, 24\]. Sulfur dioxide, predominantly emitted from fossil fuel burning and industrial processes, can cause respiratory diseases and contribute to acid rain (Kampa Castanas, 2008)\[25\]. Nitrogen dioxide, mostly released by automobiles and industrial activities, exacerbates asthma, diminishes lung function, and aggravates respiratory conditions (EPA, 2016)\[19\]. Even minimal exposure to lead significantly affects nervous system development, particularly in youngsters. Notwithstanding stringent regulations to diminish its prevalence, lead exposure remains a health hazard (Needleman, 2004; ATSDR, 2007\) \[26, 27\]. These pollutants are regulated under various environmental standards to protect human health and the ecosystem, highlighting the necessity for continuous monitoring and effective pollution management strategies. 

5  
Chapter 2\. *Literature Review* 6 2.2 Air Pollution Scenario in Bangladesh 

Bangladesh faces a critical air pollution issue, particularly in metropolitan centers like Dhaka, recognized as one of the most polluted cities globally (IQAir, 2020; World Bank, 2018\) \[28, 29\]. The rapid expansion of urban areas, heightened industrial operations, and vehicular emissions are the primary contributors to the deterioration of air quality. Brick kilns, significant sources of pollution, emit considerable quantities of particulate matter and black carbon, exacerbating the problem, especially during the dry winter months (Gurley *et al.*, 2013)\[30\]. The *PM*2*.*5 levels frequently exceed the thresholds recommended by national standards and the World Health Organization (WHO), presenting considerable health risks to the population, including respiratory and cardiovascular diseases. Seasonal variations significantly influence pollution levels since the dry season witnesses increased pollution owing to stagnant air and intensified emissions from heating and industrial activities. The government has undertaken initiatives to improve air quality. Nonetheless, the implementation and effective execution of regulations remain problematic (DoE, 2019\) \[31\]. The air pollution crisis in Bangladesh requires urgent and coordinated activities to mitigate its detrimental impacts on health and the environment, notwithstanding current governmental initiatives and international partnerships (World Bank, 2018\) 

2.3 Related works 

In recent years, technology advancements and the use of machine learning (ML) have increased. Additionally, scholars are progressively employing artificial neural networks (ANNs). Moreover, other paper-related scenarios reference CNN. The authors meticulously analyze the DL design and advance toward optimizing outputs for various challenges, including AQI classification. 

Mondal *et al.* \[32\] presented a custom Deep Convolutional Neural Network (DCNN) for location-specific *PM*2*.*5 prediction utilizing smartphone photos, which surpassed leading models such as ViT, INN, and MobileNetV2 while employing fewer parameters. This was the first publicly accessible dataset of atmospheric pictures from Dhaka, Bangladesh, facilitating further study. The model was engineered for resource efficiency, enabling practical applications in resource-limited environments and enhancing environmental monitoring, public health, and sustainability in alignment with global Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs). 

Utomo *et al.* \[33\] introduced Eff-AQI, an efficient AI model that included 1.9 million parameters for air pollution detection, surpassing leading models such as DOViT while  
Chapter 2\. *Literature Review* 7 

being considerably smaller and more resource-efficient. It attained elevated precision in estimating AQI, *PM*2*.*5, and *PM*10 and presented an innovative image-based air pollution dataset on Kaggle. The project focused on monitoring economic air quality, enhancing sustainability, and public health by aligning with SDGs 3 and 11\. 

Dao *et al.* \[34\] addressed the challenge of cost-effective and precise AQI measurement, highlighting the limitations of deploying high-end monitoring stations. They proposed a novel method to forecast AQI at both local and individual scales using smartphone-captured images and open datasets, including AQI and weather data. 

A novel image-based approach for monitoring and forecasting air quality to mitigate the health hazards associated with air pollution was presented by Sarker *et al.* \[35\]. The research established an innovative model that predicted six pollutants (*PM*2*.*5,*PM*10, O3, CO, SO2, NO2) and the AQI for Bengaluru, Delhi, and Tamil Nadu, attaining a mean absolute error of 0.1432 on the test dataset. This study utilized a selected dataset of 5,455 photos to emphasize normalization approaches and presented a real-time, user-friendly dashboard for assessing air pollution in specific locations.

2.4 Impact of *PM*2*.*5 on Optical Image 

Particulate matter (PM) in the atmosphere affects pictures via several methods, primarily through light interactions with airborne particles, such as light scattering. As previously described in studies \[49\] \[36\], this scattering includes Rayleigh scattering and Mie scattering. Light scattering diminishes light transmission in the atmosphere, mathematically represented by the Beer-Lambert equation: 

*t* \= *e−βd* (2.1) 

The symbol *d* represents the distance that light travels, whereas the symbol *β* represents the medium extinction coefficient, which depends on particle size and concentration. This formula shows we can calculate the PM concentration by determining the attenuation coefficients at various wavelengths. Several studies have shown that using well-established methods, it is possible to extract extinction coefficients from images \[50\]\[51\]\[52\] \[53\]. 

Color data, which may be essential for PM concentration predictions based on light scattering principles, are not usually considered by traditional models. Rayleigh scattering mainly happens when particles, such as air molecules, are much smaller than the wavelength of light, as shown by the *λ−*4 dependence, which explains why the sky seems blue. Mie scattering causes a white halo to form around the sun when airborne  
Chapter 2\. *Literature Review* 11 

particles interact with light at a wavelength that matches the size of the particles. The interaction between light and airborne particles determines the wavelength of light. 

Rayleigh and Mie scattering interact to affect a picture’s brightness and chromatic vibrancy. The fluctuations in colour and luminance provide significant insights into particle size and concentration, facilitating the estimation of PM levels. Incorporating color information with light attenuation is vital for precise particulate matter assessment, making it an essential characteristic for correct evaluation.

2.5.1 Transmission 

This method quantifies image distortion and the amount of light reaching the camera after being affected by airborne particles, represented by Equation 2.2 \[50\]\[51\]\[52\] \[53\]: 

*I*(*x, y*) \= *t*(*x, y*)*J*(*x, y*) \+ (1 *− t*(*x, y*))*A* (2.2) 

In this equation: 

\- *I*(*x, y*): The observed hazy image.

\- *t*(*x, y*): Scene-to-camera transmission. 

\- *J*(*x, y*): Scene radiance. 

\- *A*: Airlight color vector. 

As illustrated in Fig. 2.1, the first term *t*(*x, y*)*J*(*x, y*) represents the light transmitted from the scene to the camera lens, encompassing light reflected by scene objects and filtered by the atmosphere. The second term, (1 *− t*(*x, y*))*A*, refers to airtight, which is lightly scattered into the camera by air molecules and particulate matter (PM) \[51\]\[52\] \[53\]. 

By analyzing ROIs at different distances, Wang *et al.* \[54\] estimated light attenuation and investigated the correlation between transmission values and PM density citeliu2016particle. Nevertheless, the atmospheric and illumination conditions change with time, place, and season, and Equation 2.2 presumes they remain constant. There is a relationship between PM’s concentration, distribution, and sunshine conditions and both *J* and *A*.

4.1 Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) 

Convolutional neural networks \[56\] will analyze the pixels of the images to achieve our goal. Due to its exceptional accuracy, many deployed applications use CNN for image identification, regression analysis, and classification. The design of CNN aims to identify intricate structures in volumetric images through compactness, efficiency, and a significantly optimised network architecture. Therefore, it is crucial to analyze contemporary convolutional networks’ fundamental and adaptable components, including sophisticated convolution and enduring connection. Most modern network topologies use a fully convolutional approach. A convolutional neural network is an artificial neural network that analyses data represented visually within deep learning. CNN has positioned itself as the standard for addressing imaging issues. Their accuracy far surpasses that of their adversaries. Other applications, such as natural language processing and recommendation systems, also utilise it. The principal advantage of CNNs over preceding neural networks is their ability to identify critical elements independently without human involvement. Upon exposure to a considerable collection of images showcasing various products and animals, it can independently discern the unique characteristics of each category. Insufficient data preparation skills may lead to subpar model performance, posing a significant issue in utilising CNNs compared to conventional image applications. This is a fundamental issue that arises when using CNNs. Furthermore, CNN models may now operate on any device, enabling them to reach a broader audience. The architectural methodology of a CNN utilises pooling techniques, sophisticated convolution, and parameter sharing. Using a tensor as input, CNN may more effectively understand the spatial connections among pixels and improve performance on complex images.

The three levels are characteristic of a CNN: A convolutional layer will be included at the beginning. A layer will be established to aggregate the data in a certain way. A completely linked stratum will ultimately exist. After providing the input picture, CNN performs convolutional and pooling processes, followed by many fully connected layers. 

4.1.1.1 Convolutional Layer 

The filter of a convolutional layer does a mathematical operation on the incoming data. It is considered the most essential element of the whole procedure. The convolutional layer first accepts the picture as input. Subsequently, it performs a mathematical operation using its 3x3 kernel. The convolutional procedure often transpires inside the receptive field. The receptive field was a 3x3 matrix because it used a 3x3 kernel. The input undergoes convolution by moving the kernel across it, and the feature map illustrates the total of the outcomes from component-wise matrix multiplication at each place. 

4.1.1.2 Activation Function 

It fundamentally aids in ascertaining if a neuron or node should be triggered, contingent upon certain mathematical conditions. It generally assesses the relevance of the information from a prior node and decides its integration into the network using specific mathematical processes. 

4.1.1.3 ReLU Activation 

For a neural network to function effectively, non-linearity is essential. This is achieved by applying the ReLU activation function to the result of the convolution operation. Instead of simply summing the values, the ReLU function processes the feature maps. 

ReLU activation introduces non-linearity by replacing all negative values in the feature map with 0 while leaving positive values unchanged. This behaviour is defined mathematically by the following equation and illustrated in Fig. 4.1. 

*f*(*x*) \= max(0*, x*) (4.1)

4.1.1.5 Pooling 

The pooling layer reduces the dimension of the feature map. The feature map is used to execute the pooling procedure. A 2-pixel by 2-pixel spatial neighborhood is first chosen for pooling. We can support any window size for pooling. In this instance, we have used two to two windows for aggregation. We exclude the other three items and choose the most significant value from the pooling window of the feature map. This technique preserves the relevance of the traits. During pooling, unnecessary pixels are discarded, while essential pixels are retained. Consequently, by merging, we may reduce the size of the feature map, thereby enhancing the effectiveness of our program.

4.1.1.8 Filters 

A filter (a kernel) is a window traverses an image to evaluate certain aspects. Filters aid in identifying the category to which a pixel is assigned, such as an arc, a straight line, or a diagonal. Filters are designed trecogniseze specific characteristics; for instance, one may discern arcs, while another may distinguish diagonal lines. The filter or kernel dimensions dictate the size of the zone since the filters examine the picture segment by segment. 

• Filter Dimensions: 

Larger filters like 5×5 or 7×7 may be applied depending on the objective. Additionally, 1×1 filters are sometimes utilized. Despite their atypical nature, they offer unique and beneficial applications. 

• Number of Filters: 

Two, ranging from 32 to 1024\. Using more filters allows the model to capture more intricate features; however, it increases the possibility of overfitting due to the higher number of parameters. Typically, the network begins with fewer filters in the initial layers and gradually increases the count in the deeper layers to capture more abstract information.

4.1.1.9 Stride 

In a convolutional neural network, stride refers to the number of pixels that may be shifted during each convolution operation. A filter window is inherently available during convolution and may be shifted by one pixel in either the x direction or y direction. This is designated as a stride of 1 by 1\. The filter window will change by two pixels in either the x direction or y direction when a 2x2 stride is used. The default trajectory is one by one. The input picture undergoes a filter matrix application, yielding a feature map with reduced dimensions. Padding refers to the method of reducing the dimensions of the input picture. Consequently, the input image’s dimensions are reduced by the margin, yielding a feature map of lesser size. Fig. 4.4 shows how stride works. 

4.1.1.10 Padding 

The term ”padding” is essential in CNNs since it denotes the number of pixels included in an image during processing by the CNN kernel. If the padding in a CNN is set to 0, each subsequent pixel value will similarly be zero. We thoroughly use the available cushioning dimension. If we add a border of pixels with zero, it will be called a zero padding layer. A border of pixels filled with zeros is added by this layer. Zeroes will be positioned at the edges of a picture. Figure 4.5 depicts the various output dimensions that may arise from convolving our input when adding a boundary of zero-valued pixels. An approach that enables the preservation of the original data input is zero buffering.

4.2.1 ResNet-50 

Residual networks or ResNets \[58\], capture residual functions by examining each layer’s inputs rather than directly learning the fundamental functions. ResNets enable stacked layers to focus on the optimisation of residual mappings. The design does this by integrating skip connections, allowing information to bypass certain levels, thereby enhancing the learning process. Fig. 4.6 shows the basic diagram block of the resnet-50 model architecture.  
Chapter 4\. *Model Background* 27 

Fig. 4.6. Model Architecture of ResNet50. 

ResNet-50, as its name suggests, is a deep neural network built with 50 layers of convolutional operation units. The whole network is constructed by sequentially stacking these units. We redefine residual mapping as the desired mapping, representing the difference between a block’s input and output. This strategy has proven effective in enhancing network optimization and allowing for increased depth without significant performance deterioration since skip connections alleviate problems like disappearing gradients. 

4.2.2 VGG-19 

The VGG network architecture was first introduced in 2014 \[59\], and VGG19 is a variant of it. With 16 convolutional layers, 5 MaxPooling layers, 3 fully connected layers, and 1 SoftMax layer, VGG19 achieves a total of 19 layers. Building upon its predecessors, it

With a compound coefficient and a scaling mechanism, EfficientNet is a CNN model design that constantly changes width, depth, and resolution. The model is successful because of its simplicity and unique scaling technique. An automated neural architecture search methodology is used, which significantly enhances efficiency and precision. By reducing floating-point operations per second, the model improves the overall performance compared to the other models \[60\]. The EfficientNet framework can achieve good accuracy, compactness, and efficiency. With 23,534,592 parameters, Keras’s ResNet50 model outperforms the most miniature EfficientNet model, which uses only 5,330,564 parameters. One of the essential components of EfficientNet is the Inverted Bottleneck (MBConv), first presented in MobileNet models. It reduces the model complexity by connecting the bottlenecks and the depthwise separable convolution layers. 

4.2.4 MobileNetV2 

MobileNetV2 \[61\], a CNN architecture primarily developed for use on mobile devices, is also an exemplary architecture for classification tasks and is known for image-processing functionalities. It is also available on TensorFlow for transfer learning purposes. It is maintained and updated by Google. MobileNetV2 is built with a modified residual architecture where some residual connections are present with the bottleneck levels. MobileNetV2 is built around a modified residual architecture with residual connections among bottleneck levels. Layers in the hidden levels are so lightweight that computational expenses are saved. It comprises an initial convolutional layer, including 32 channels and 19 bottleneck layers. 

The main characteristic of this model is that it can transform low-level information, like pixels, lines, etc, into higher-level representations, such as classifications. On the other hand, residual connections (shortcuts) improve the accuracy and accelerate the training process. 

4.2.5 Inception V3 

InceptionV3, a (CNN) model, is designed for producing label information at the intermediate level by adding an auxiliary classifier employing factorized 7*×*7 convolutions and utilizing label smoothing. Besides, it normalizes the bulk layers in the auxiliary head. It is mainly helpful for greater computational efficiency and the maximization of resource utilization \[62\]. Factorized convolutions, parallel calculations, regularisation,

dimensionality reduction, etc, are the main ways the Inception model uses to maintain efficiency. In the preliminary phase, the model decreases the parameter count by the factorized convolutions. Then, the bigger conv layers are replaced by the smaller ones. The computational complexity may be lowered by substituting a 3 *×* 3 convolution with a 1 *×* 3 convolution followed by a 3 *×* 1 convolution. Conversely, substituting a 3 *×* 3 convolution with a 2 *×* 2 convolution may result in a little increase in the parameter count. 

The design includes a diminutive CNN inside the auxiliary classifier, which functions between layers and introduces supplementary loss terms to assist the core network during training. Finally, pooling techniques enhance the model’s efficiency and architecture by diminishing the grid’s dimensions. These strategies combined enable InceptionV3 to sustain resource efficiency while attaining superior performance.

Vision Transformers are image classification models that use Transformer principles to assess visual data. The architecture partitions an image into segments of a specified size upon receiving it as input. Fig. 4.8 shows the basic architecture block of Vision Transformer.

4.2.7 Involutional Neural Network (INN) 

Convolution is the foundation for most modern neural networks in computer vision applications. Classical convolution uses a channel-specific, space-invariant kernel to process data no matter where it is physically located. This trait, although practical, limits its ability to handle diverse visual patterns linked to specific geographical locations. The limited receptive area further hinders capturing long-range spatial relationships in convolution. 

Li *et al.* \[65\] proposed the ”Involution kernel,” an innovative operation independent of channels and particular locations to address these challenges. The Involution kernel, unlike traditional convolution, can adjust to spatial locations. This paradigm is consistent with what the authors call ”self-attention processes.” 

Take *X*, a tensor with dimensions *H*, *W*, and *C*in, as an example of an input into an involution. In convolution, ( C˙out is employed, which is a set of kernels with dimensions *K × K × C*in. Through the use of the input tensor and the kernels in a multiply-add operation, the resulting output tensor *Y* is generated with dimensions *H*, *W*, and *C*out. The resultant tensor is geometrically defined as *H × W ×* 3\. The value of C˙out is 3, where Each output channel has its own distinct convolution filter, which is spatially ˙ independent, according to conventional convolution kernels, which are channel-specific \[65\]. 

The goal of Involution is to establish an operation that is autonomous from both channel and location. Implementing these features poses a considerable problem, especially when handling variable-resolution input tensors. In such cases, traditional fixed kernels cannot accommodate spatial fluctuations. 

The authors proposed the generation of kernels tailored to specific geographical locations to resolve this problem. This approach facilitates the efficient processing of variable-resolution tensors by creating *K × K ×C* filters with *C* denoting the number of channel groups. Figure 4.12 demonstrates that the approach produces *C* unique filters and transmits each to its respective input channel rather than using a single filter across all *C* input channels. This invention boosts spatial adaptation and increases flexibility in neural networks.

7.1 General Discussion 

In the prior sections, we disclosed our results on predicting PM2*.*5 using deep learning techniques. The dataset that we have collected is comparatively balanced, a crucial characteristic of real-world data. A *R*2score over 0.3 shows the model’s effectiveness on real-world data. The model’s efficacy diminishes when applied to photographs taken outside Dhaka City since its training data is solely based on the city’s surroundings, resulting in difficulties with disordered images. So, our proposed model won’t be able to recognize any pictures collected from outside Dhaka, which sets a significant limitation of the model. 

The limited size of the test dataset affects the correlation coefficient, leading to outcomes that fall short of expectations. This is another limitation of our investigation. 7.2 Techniques for Optimization 

We used zero-padding, discussed in Chapter ??, to maintain the dimensions of the feature maps across the network and to retain edge information. This strategy enhances the model’s performance by preventing a sudden decrease in volume. Additionally, by highlighting essential traits and minimizing the number of factors, MaxPooling improves prediction accuracy and reduces computing costs. In contrast to Average Pooling, which averages characteristics, MaxPooling yields more accurate outcomes. We limited the number of nodes in the dense layer to improve the optimization process, avoiding duplication and maintaining similar performance. 

7.3 Comparative Performance 

Our Deep CNN (DCNN) exhibited enhanced performance compared to attention-based models, including Vision Transformers (ViTs) and Involution Networks (INNs). Vision Transformers (ViTs) excel in object recognition and segmentation because they can partition images into distinct segments. Nonetheless, they failed in this endeavor since AQI prediction relies on the whole picture rather than specific areas. Although ViTs are adapted for regression problems \[66\]\[67\], they face challenges in this application. Contrarily, INNs are location-specific and not channel-dependent.\[65\]. This implies they cannot forecast AQI, as AQI remains independent of specific spatial or color-channel data. 

7.4 Model Sensitivity 

Flipuk *et al.* \[68\] discovered that Vision Transformers (ViTs) are more susceptible to noise and contrast loss despite their apparent resistance to some disturbances. This sensitivity makes it harder to find AQIs because man-made things often stand out from their surroundings in a big way. Chen *et al.* \[69\] highlight the vulnerability of ViTs to noise and outliers, adversely impacting their performance in this context.  
Chapter 7\. *Discussion* 47 

Concurrently, DCNNs have shown superior proficiency in handling ambiguous features and noise, making them more suitable for this problem. 

In conclusion, our custom DCNN surpassed previous models, especially in AQI prediction from photos, demonstrating its effectiveness and appropriateness for this purpose.

8.1 Conclusion 

Researchers have a hard time figuring out how to predict the levels of particulate matter *PM*2*.*5 from pictures because it’s hard to tell how different objects at different depths affect visibility. To complete this work, we must comprehensively comprehend the image content and how it relates to air quality measures. By developing our own customized Deep Convolutional Neural Network, we’ve proposed a way to predict the amounts of *PM*2*.*5 contained in photos which will eventually give an idea of the location’s air quality. 

The images used on the dataset\[32\] were collected so that images with at least fifty percent of the sky were visible to ensure consistency. The lower part of the images was cropped, except for the sky, to eliminate any unnecessary components. After preprocessing these images, we trained on the proposed CNN and other pre-trained models. The result of our experiment shows that the saturation level of an image can dramatically affect the prediction of the particulate matter (*PM*2*.*5) in the air. So, it can be said that the data collection process and resources are the most critical steps for this research. 

A supervised learning method was used to train the CNN model. The dataset of 1,818 images, each tagged with a matching *PM*2*.*5 value and the associated Air Quality Index (AQI) values during the photos’ collection, helped train the CNN model in a supervised way. The experiment gave us a comprehensive view of the connection between the air quality and the image property, which was taken in the open air. This experiment showed that CNNs could accurately project *PM*2*.*5 concentrations, but it will require more data with a proper image-capturing device to increase the accuracy. As the trustability and the interpretability of a model is a concerning issue, it’s essential to know the 

52

learning process of the black box deep learning models, so we used Explainable AI (XAI) techniques like Grad-CAM and LIME to make the model’s predictions more interpretable and understandable. These tools helped to visualize parts of the images that were learnt during the training process and, most important, made the impact in determining the *PM*2*.*5 levels. The transparency and the confidence of the model’s decision-making were improved by these tools. 8.2 Limitations 

Specific conditions can significantly impact the result of processing and models when working with image data. For instance, images featuring bright or direct sunlight reflections frequently exhibit excessive luminosity, complicating the model’s predictions and distorting the scene. Similarly, the inability to view nocturnal photos is often the consequence of the low quality of the image and the low light conditions. This experimental model is not yet ready for use at night since its primary design is solely for monitoring air quality during the day (till dusk). 

The quality and resolution of the images also have a substantial impact on the model’s efficacy. High-resolution photos are indispensable because each pixel contributes critical information to the prediction process. Cameras that capture low-resolution images may introduce noise, leading to distorted results. Noisy data can significantly impair the precision of predictions, frequently resulting in unfavorable outcomes. Additionally, many modern smartphones utilize computational photography techniques that approximate images rather than capture absolute photon values. This can introduce inaccuracies in the data and modify pixel-level details, thereby impacting model predictions \[70\]. 

Furthermore, most smartphones design their images as ”social media-ready,” emphasizing aesthetic enhancements like brightness and contrast adjustments to increase appeal. These automatic adjustments frequently compromise the reliability of the data for scientific purposes by distorting the actual visual representation of the scene. Although these manipulations benefit social media utilization, they introduce biases into the dataset, negatively affecting the model’s ability to make accurate predictions. To get around these problems, we need to carefully look at the data collection process,  
*References* 54 

using cameras made for scientific accuracy and setting up standard conditions for taking pictures. Since the images were collected from different mobile phone users, the standard of the data sampling remains a big issue for the output of the proposed model. 

8.3 Future work 

Our future aims are to extend the dataset by collecting images from different regions all over Bangladesh, including transforming the current model into a transfer learning framework to use its capabilities for other relevant jobs. Additionally, we want to implement the model as a mobile application, aligning with our goal of guaranteeing its applicability in real-world scenarios. To enhance the robustness of our methodology, we will persist in gathering an extensive collection of photos and their associated *PM*2*.*5 values using AQI detection sensors. 

Furthermore, advanced methodology, like ensembling different trained models and merging their output, can improve the overall result; we want to assess and test advanced models to improve their efficacy. We will perform comparison studies under various meteorological situations to enhance the model’s accuracy and gain a comprehensive understanding of its behavior. Furthermore, we will explore innovative methods to preprocess and structure picture data to improve its suitability as input for deep learning models, ensuring optimal results for this job.
